== Cardiovascular Diseases

=== Congenital Heart Disease (CHD)

*Classification*:  
- *Acyanotic CHD* (Left → Right shunt, obstructive lesions):  
  - VSD, ASD, PDA, AV canal defect  
  - Pulmonary stenosis (mild), Aortic stenosis, Coarctation of Aorta  
- *Cyanotic CHD* (Right → Left shunt):  
  - Tetralogy of Fallot (TOF) [most common cyanotic CHD]  
  - Transposition of Great Arteries (TGA)  
  - Tricuspid atresia, TAPVR, Truncus arteriosus, Hypoplastic left heart  

==== Tetralogy of Fallot (TOF)
*Components*:  
1. VSD  
2. Overriding aorta  
3. Pulmonary stenosis  
4. RV hypertrophy  

*Clinical features*:  
- Cyanosis (appears later in mild PS)  
- “Tet spells” (cyanotic spells after exertion/crying)  
- Clubbing in older children  
- Squatting position (↑ SVR, ↓ R-L shunt, relieves cyanosis)  
- Harsh ejection systolic murmur (PS)  

*Management*:  
- Acute cyanotic spell → knee-chest position, O2, IV fluids, morphine, beta-blocker (propranolol), emergency surgical care if refractory.  
- Definitive surgery → complete intracardiac repair (usually after 6 months).  

==== Ventricular Septal Defect (VSD)
*Clinical features*:  
- Small VSD: asymptomatic, loud pansystolic murmur at LLSB  
- Large VSD: CHF in infancy (tachypnea, poor weight gain, frequent LRTI)  
- Complications: Eisenmenger syndrome (late cyanosis due to reversal of shunt), growth failure  

*Management*:  
- Small: may close spontaneously, observe.  
- Large: diuretics, ACE inhibitors, high-calorie feeds; surgical closure if symptomatic/large defect not closing.  



=== Heart Failure in Children
*Causes*: Large L→R shunt CHDs, myocarditis, cardiomyopathy, severe anemia, arrhythmias.  

*Clinical Features*:  
- Tachypnea, feeding difficulty, hepatomegaly, poor weight gain, sweating during feeds.  

*Management Principles*:  
- Treat underlying cause (CHD, arrhythmia, anemia, infection)  
- Improve cardiac function: Diuretics (furosemide), ACE inhibitors (captopril), Digoxin (in selected cases)  
- Improve nutrition: Frequent, energy-dense feeds  
- Oxygen supplementation if hypoxic  
- Correct anemia, electrolyte imbalance  



=== Rheumatic Fever and Rheumatic Heart Disease (RHD)

*Jones Criteria (Revised)* → *Diagnosis = Evidence of preceding GAS infection + 2 major OR 1 major + 2 minor*  

- *Major criteria*:  
  - Carditis (clinical/echo)  
  - Polyarthritis (migratory, large joints)  
  - Chorea (Sydenham)  
  - Erythema marginatum  
  - Subcutaneous nodules  

- *Minor criteria*:  
  - Fever  
  - Arthralgia  
  - Raised ESR/CRP  
  - Prolonged PR interval  

*Evidence of GAS infection*: Positive throat culture, rapid antigen test, or ↑ ASO/anti-DNase B titers.  

*Diagnosis*: Based on Jones criteria + evidence of recent strep infection. Commonly presents in school-aged children after untreated pharyngitis.  

*Management*:  
- *Acute Rheumatic Fever*:  
  - Bed rest, supportive care  
  - Eradication of GAS: Benzathine penicillin IM (single dose) / Penicillin V oral 10 days  
  - Anti-inflammatory: Aspirin (for arthritis), Corticosteroids (if carditis with HF)  
  - Heart failure management: Diuretics, ACE inhibitors, digoxin if needed  

- *Rheumatic Heart Disease (Chronic)*:  
  - Valvular involvement (esp. Mitral > Aortic)  
  - Medical management of HF, surgical correction (valvotomy/valve replacement) as indicated  

*Primary Prophylaxis*:  
- Treatment of each episode of GAS pharyngitis with penicillin to prevent ARF.  

*Secondary Prophylaxis*:  
- Long-term benzathine penicillin IM injection every 3-4 weeks  
- Duration:  
  - Carditis + residual heart disease → at least 10 yrs or until age 40  
  - Carditis, but no residual disease → 10 yrs or until age 21  
  - No carditis → 5 yrs or until age 21  
== Gastrointestinal and Liver Diseases

=== Hepatosplenomegaly
*Differential Diagnoses in a Child*:  
- *Infective*: Malaria, Kala-azar, Enteric fever, EBV, CMV, HIV  
- *Hematological*: Hemolytic anemia (Thalassemia), Leukemia, Lymphoma  
- *Storage/Metabolic*: Gaucher, Niemann-Pick, Wilson disease  
- *Cardiac*: Congestive cardiac failure, Constrictive pericarditis  
- *Liver diseases*: Viral hepatitis, Cirrhosis, Chronic cholestasis  

*Investigations*:  
- CBC + peripheral smear, Reticulocyte count (anemia, hemolysis, leukemia)  
- LFT, Viral markers (HAV, HBV, HCV, EBV, CMV)  
- USG abdomen (organ size, texture, ascites, lymph nodes, masses)  
- Bone marrow aspirate/biopsy if malignancy suspected  
- Specific tests: Malaria antigen/smear, rk39 (Kala-azar), Coombs test, Serum ceruloplasmin (Wilson), Genetic tests for storage disorders  



=== Viral Hepatitis
*Common causes*: HAV, HBV, HCV, HDV, HEV  

*Diagnosis*:  
- Clinical features → fever, malaise, anorexia, jaundice, hepatomegaly  
- LFTs → ↑SGPT/ALT, ↑bilirubin, ↑ALP, deranged INR if severe  
- Viral serology (IgM anti-HAV, HBsAg, HBeAg, Anti-HBc, Anti-HCV, Anti-HEV etc.)  
- Exclude other causes (autoimmune hepatitis, Wilson disease)  

*Management*:  
- Supportive: Bed rest, adequate nutrition, hydration, avoid hepatotoxic drugs  
- Antiviral therapy (in chronic HBV/HCV as per guidelines)  
- Treatment of complications (encephalopathy, bleed)  
- Monitoring with LFTs and INR  

*Complications*:  
- Fulminant hepatic failure → encephalopathy, cerebral edema, bleeding diathesis, multi-organ failure  
- Chronic HBV/HCV → cirrhosis, hepatocellular carcinoma  



=== Chronic Liver Disease (CLD) in Children
*Stigmata*:  
- Jaundice, hepatosplenomegaly  
- Ascites, caput medusae, prominent abdominal veins  
- Spider nevi, palmar erythema, clubbing  
- Growth faltering, delayed puberty  
- Gynecomastia, testicular atrophy (adolescents)  
- Fetor hepaticus, asterixis (advanced disease)  

*Management of complications*:  

- *Hematemsis due to varices*:  
  - Initial resuscitation: Ensure airway, large bore IV line, fluid resuscitation, blood transfusion as needed  
  - Pharmacological: IV octreotide or terlipressin  
  - Endoscopic: Endoscopic variceal ligation (EVL) or sclerotherapy  
  - Balloon tamponade if uncontrolled bleeding  
  - Long-term: Non-selective beta-blockers (propranolol), repeated EVL, shunt surgery or TIPS in refractory cases  
- *Ascites*: Salt restriction, spironolactone ± furosemide, paracentesis if tense ascites, albumin infusion if hypoproteinemia  
- *Hepatic encephalopathy*: Lactulose, rifaximin, treat precipitating factors (GI bleed, infection, hypokalemia, constipation)  
- *Nutrition support*: High-calorie, adequate protein diet (restrict only during encephalopathy)  
- *Definitive*: Liver transplantation if decompensated CLD  



=== Ascites
*Differential Diagnosis in a Child*:  
- *Hepatic causes*: CLD, Budd-Chiari syndrome, Congenital hepatic fibrosis  
- *Cardiac causes*: Right heart failure, Constrictive pericarditis  
- *Renal causes*: Nephrotic syndrome  
- *Malignant/neoplastic causes*: Peritoneal carcinomatosis, Lymphoma  
- *Infective causes*: Tuberculous peritonitis, SBP (spontaneous bacterial peritonitis)  

*Investigations*:  
- Clinical: Ascitic fluid wave/shifting dullness, hepatosplenomegaly, edema  
- Ultrasound abdomen (ascites, liver/spleen size, portal hypertension, masses)  
- Ascitic fluid analysis:  
  - SAAG (serum-ascites albumin gradient): >1.1 g/dL → portal hypertension (hepatic, cardiac); < 1.1 → peritoneal causes (TB, malignancy)  
  - Cell count & culture (SBP if neutrophils >250/mm³)  
  - Microscopy, cytology, ADA (TB)  
- LFT, RFT, urine analysis (nephrotic syndrome), Echocardiography (cardiac causes), Chest X-ray (TB, CHF)  
