== Neurological Disorders

=== Seizures and Epilepsy

==== Febrile Seizures
*Diagnostic Criteria*:  
- Age: 6 months - 5 years  
- Seizure with fever (>38°C) not due to CNS infection/metabolic disturbance  
- Generalized tonic-clonic (commonly), usually < 15 min (simple febrile seizure)  
- No prior afebrile seizures; development and neuro exam otherwise normal  

*Types*:  
- *Simple FS*: Generalized, < 15 min, single in 24h, no neuro deficit  
- *Complex FS*: Focal features, >15 min, or recurrent within 24h  

*Management*:  
- During episode: Protect airway, place child on side, do not restrain, no putting objects in mouth  
- Antipyretics for fever (but don't actually prevent recurrence of seizures)  
- No long-term anticonvulsants for simple febrile seizures  
- If seizure prolonged (>5 min) → benzodiazepine (diazepam, lorazepam)  
- Educate parents about benign nature, recurrence risk (~30%), very low risk of epilepsy  

*Differentiation from meningitis/encephalitis*:  
- Presence of meningeal signs (neck stiffness, photophobia, bulging fontanelle if infant)  
- Altered consciousness beyond post-ictal state  
- Focal neuro deficit  
- Persistent vomiting, irritability  
- CSF studies confirm CNS infection  



==== Status Epilepticus
*Definition*: Seizure >5 minutes OR ≥ 2 seizures without regaining consciousness in between.  

*Management Protocol*:  
- *0-5 min (Stabilization)*: ABCs, secure airway, high-flow oxygen, monitor BP, O₂ sat, IV access, dextrose if hypoglycemia suspected  
- *5-20 min (Emergent therapy)*: IV/rectal Lorazepam (0.1 mg/kg), Diazepam, or Midazolam  
- *20-40 min (Urgent therapy)*: IV phenytoin/fosphenytoin, Valproate, Levetiracetam  
- *40-60 min (Refractory status)*: IV phenobarbital, midazolam infusion, ICU care, ventilation support  
- Identify and treat underlying causes (infection, metabolic, trauma, toxic, structural)  



=== Meningitis

*Clinical Features*:  
- Fever, headache, vomiting  
- Meningeal signs: neck stiffness, kernig's sign, photophobia  
- Altered consciousness, irritability, seizures  
- Infants: bulging fontanelle, poor feeding, lethargy  

*CSF Findings for Differentiation*:  
- *Bacterial*: ↑↑ protein, ↓ glucose (< 40% of serum), ↑↑ neutrophils, turbid CSF  
- *Viral*: Mild ↑ protein, normal glucose, lymphocytic predominance, clear CSF  
- *Tubercular*: Very high protein, very low glucose, lymphocytic predominance, fibrin web; AFB/GeneXpert positive  

*Management*:  
- Empirical antibiotics (IV cefotaxime/ceftriaxone + vancomycin; add ampicillin in neonates/elderly)  
- Dexamethasone (reduces hearing loss in Hib meningitis)  
- Supportive: manage seizures, hydration, ICP management  
- Tubercular meningitis → HRZE + prolonged steroids  
- Viral → supportive unless HSV (IV acyclovir)  



=== Cerebral Palsy
*Definition*: Permanent, non-progressive motor impairment due to abnormal brain development or early injury.  

*Clinical features*:  
- Abnormal tone (spastic, dyskinetic, ataxic subtypes)  
- Delayed motor milestones  
- Associated: seizures, intellectual disability, sensory impairments (hearing/vision), feeding difficulties  

*Differential for motor problems in child*:  
- Neuromuscular disorders (Muscular dystrophy, Myopathy, SMA)  
- CNS structural/migrational defects  
- Metabolic encephalopathies  
- Hypothyroidism, chronic systemic illness  
- Orthopedic conditions (hip dysplasia, rickets)  

*Management*:  
- Multidisciplinary → physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy  
- Antispasticity → baclofen, diazepam, botulinum toxin  
- Manage associated problems (antiepileptics, vision/hearing aids, nutritional support)  



=== Acute Flaccid Paralysis (AFP)

==== Guillain-Barré Syndrome (GBS)
*Definition*: Post-infectious acute demyelinating polyneuropathy with ascending flaccid paralysis.  

*Clinical Features*:  
- Ascending weakness, areflexia  
- Sensory involvement mild  
- Cranial nerve involvement possible (facial palsy)  
- Autonomic dysfunction (arrhythmias, BP fluctuation)  
- Preceded by infection (Campylobacter, CMV, EBV)  

*Investigation*:  
- Nerve conduction studies (demyelinating pattern)  
- CSF: albuminocytologic dissociation (↑ protein, normal cells) after 1 week  

*Management*:  
- Admit, monitor vitals & respiratory function (FVC, NIF)  
- IVIG or Plasmapheresis shortens course  
- Supportive: prevent complications (DVT, infection, contractures)  
- Steroids not beneficial  

==== Poliomyelitis
*Definition*: Viral (poliovirus) infection causing anterior horn cell destruction → asymmetric flaccid paralysis.  

*Clinical Features*:  
- Prodrome: fever, sore throat, myalgia  
- Acute onset asymmetric flaccid paralysis  
- Reflexes absent in affected limb, sensation preserved  
- May cause bulbar paralysis → respiratory failure  

*Diagnosis*:  
- Stool viral culture/PCR  
- AFP surveillance programs  

*Management*:  
- No specific antiviral treatment  
- Supportive care: respiratory support, physiotherapy, orthopedic management  
- *Prevention is key*: OPV & IPV vaccination under EPI  


== Hematological Disorders
=== Thaassemia
*Clinical Features*
- Pallor, progressive anemia
- Failure to thrive, irritability
- Splenomegaly, hepatomegaly
- Extramedullary hematopoiesis → frontal bossing, maxillary hypertrophy, “chipmunk facies”
- Growth retardation, delayed puberty, bone deformities
- Recurrent infections (if post-splenectomy)
*Blood picture*
- CBC: Microcytic hypochromic anemia, very low MCV/MCH
- Peripheral smear: Target cells, nucleated RBCs, anisopoikilocytosis, basophilic stippling
- Reticulocytosis (variable)
- Confirmatory: Hb electrophoresis/HPLC → ↑ HbF and/or HbA₂
*Complications of Transfusions*
- Iron overload → cardiomyopathy, liver cirrhosis, endocrinopathies (diabetes, hypogonadism)
- Transfusion reactions (febrile, allergic, hemolytic)
- Alloimmunization
- Infections (Hepatitis B, C, HIV - rare with modern screening)
*Genetic Counselling*
- Autosomal recessive disorder → importance of carrier detection
- Hb electrophoresis/HPLC for parents & siblings
- Prenatal diagnosis: DNA analysis / CVS at 10-12 weeks
- Advise carrier couples on risk of affected offspring
- Population screening programs for prevention
=== Iron Deficiency Anemia
*Causes*
- Nutritional deficiency (low dietary iron)
- Increased demand (infancy, adolescence, pregnancy)
- Blood loss (GI bleed, hookworm, menorrhagia)
- Malabsorption (celiac disease)
*Investigation*
- CBC: Microcytic hypochromic anemia
- Peripheral smear: Target cells, anisopoikilocytosis
- Serum ferritin ↓, serum iron ↓, TIBC ↑
- Reticulocyte count ↓ (unless on iron therapy)
*Management in Children*
- Oral elemental iron 3-6 mg/kg/day for 3-6 months after Hb normalization
- Treat underlying cause (anthelmintics, diet improvement)
- Parenteral iron if oral intolerance/malabsorption
- Nutritional counseling + iron-rich foods
=== Leukemia (especially ALL)
*Clinical Presentation*
- Anemia: Pallor, fatigue
- Bleeding: Petechiae, purpura, epistaxis
- Infections: Fever, recurrent infections (due to neutropenia)
- Organomegaly: Hepatomegaly, splenomegaly, lymphadenopathy
- Bone pain, irritability
- CNS involvement (headache, vomiting, cranial nerve palsies)
*Blood Picture*
- Pancytopenia (anemia, thrombocytopenia, neutropenia)
- WBC: high/low/normal but blasts present
- Peripheral smear: Lymphoblasts
- Bone marrow: Hypercellular, >25% lymphoblasts
*Principles of Treatment*
- Induction of remission (multi-drug chemotherapy)
- Consolidation/intensification
- CNS prophylaxis (intrathecal chemo ± cranial irradiation)
- Maintenance therapy
- Supportive care: Transfusions, antibiotics, management of tumor lysis
=== Idiopathic Thrombocytopenic Purpura(ITP)
*Diagnosis*
- Isolated thrombocytopenia (platelets < 100,000)
- Normal WBC and Hb (unless bleeding-induced anemia)
- Peripheral smear: Reduced platelets, morphology otherwise normal
- Bone marrow: Normal/increased megakaryocytes (done if diagnosis in doubt)
- Exclusion of secondary causes (SLE, HIV, drugs)
*Management*
- No treatment if platelets >30,000 and no significant bleeding
- First-line: Oral corticosteroids / IVIG
- Anti-D immunoglobulin (in Rh+)
- Refractory: Rituximab, azathioprine, splenectomy
- Supportive: Platelet transfusion only if life-threatening bleed
=== Hemophilia
*Diagnosis*
- Clinical: Recurrent hemarthrosis, muscle bleeds, prolonged bleeding after trauma/surgery
- Labs:
  - Prolonged APTT
  - Normal PT, bleeding time, platelet count
- Specific factor assay: Reduced Factor VIII (Hemophilia A) or IX (Hemophilia B)
*Management of Bleeding Episodes*
- Replace deficient factor (Factor VIII or IX concentrate)
- If concentrates unavailable: Cryoprecipitate (VIII) or FFP (IX)
- Adjuncts: Tranexamic acid for mucosal bleeds
- Avoid IM injections, NSAIDs, and aspirin
- Physiotherapy post-bleed to preserve joint function
== Endocrine and Genetic Disorders

=== Congenital Hypothyroidism
*Clinical Features*:  
- Subtle in neonates (screening important)  
- Prolonged jaundice  
- Lethargy, poor feeding, constipation  
- Hypotonia  
- Dysmorphic: macroglossia, coarse facies, large fontanelles, umbilical hernia  
- Hoarse cry, hypothermia, dry skin  
- If untreated → growth retardation, intellectual disability (cretinism)  

*Management*:  
- *Levothyroxine* 10-15 µg/kg/day orally, *start ASAP* (ideally within 2 weeks of life)  
- Monitoring: TSH + T4 every 2-3 months in infancy, then every 3-6 months  
- Lifelong treatment in permanent forms  
- Early diagnosis + treatment → near-normal growth, neurodevelopment, and IQ  



=== Genetic Syndromes

==== Down Syndrome (Trisomy 21)
*Etiology*: Nondisjunction (95%), Robertsonian translocation, mosaicism.  

*Clinical Features*:  
- Characteristic facies: flat nasal bridge, upslanting palpebral fissures, epicanthic folds, small mouth with protruding tongue, low-set ears  
- Hypotonia in infancy, developmental delay, short stature  
- Hands: single palmar crease, clinodactyly, sandal gap  
- Congenital heart disease (AV canal defect, VSD, PDA)  
- GI: duodenal atresia, Hirschsprung disease  
- Hematological: ↑ risk of ALL, transient myeloproliferative disorder in neonates  
- Endocrine: Hypothyroidism common  
- Others: Atlanto-axial instability, recurrent respiratory infections, early-onset Alzheimer's  

*Management*:  
- Early intervention: physiotherapy, speech & occupational therapy  
- Regular health screening: cardiac echo, TSH, vision/hearing, hematology  
- Surgical correction for CHD/GI anomalies  
- Multidisciplinary rehab, family counseling  



==== Turner Syndrome (45,XO or variants)
*Etiology*: Complete/partial loss of one X chromosome.  

*Clinical Features*:  
- Short stature  
- Webbed neck, low posterior hairline  
- Broad shield chest with widely spaced nipples  
- Cubitus valgus  
- Neonatal lymphedema (hands/feet)  
- Primary amenorrhea, infertility (streak ovaries)  
- Normal intelligence (may have math/spatial learning issues)  
- Cardiac: coarctation of aorta, bicuspid aortic valve  
- Renal anomalies: horseshoe kidney  
- Endocrine: hypothyroidism, osteoporosis risk  

*Management*:  
- Growth hormone therapy in childhood to improve final height  
- Estrogen replacement at puberty (induces secondary sexual characteristics, prevents osteoporosis)  
- Cardiac and renal screening  
- Fertility counseling; ART with donor eggs possible  
- Psychosocial support and educational help as needed  



==== Klinefelter Syndrome (47,XXY)
*Etiology*: Extra X chromosome in males.  

*Clinical Features*:  
- Tall stature, long extremities  
- Gynecomastia  
- Small, firm testes → hypogonadism  
- Infertility (azoospermia, testicular atrophy)  
- Sparse body and facial hair  
- Learning difficulties, psychosocial/behavioral problems possible  
- ↑ risk of: breast cancer, osteoporosis, metabolic syndrome  

*Management*:  
- Testosterone replacement therapy (improves virilization, muscle mass, bone density)  
- Fertility counseling (rarely possible with ART)  
- Psychosocial, speech, and educational support  
- Screen for metabolic syndrome, osteoporosis, malignancies  



