=== Rickets

*Definition*: A metabolic bone disease in children characterized by defective mineralization of growing bone and cartilage at the epiphyseal growth plates, most often due to *Vitamin D deficiency*.

*Causes (Vitamin D Deficiency Rickets)*:  
- *Nutritional deficiency*:  
  - Inadequate sunlight exposure  
  - Exclusive prolonged breastfeeding without supplementation  
  - Poor dietary intake (low vitamin D, calcium, phosphate)  
- *Malabsorption syndromes*:  
  - Celiac disease  
  - Cystic fibrosis  
  - Chronic liver or biliary disease (cholestasis)  
- *Chronic renal disease* (impaired vitamin D activation, phosphate loss)  
- *Medications*: Anticonvulsants (phenytoin, phenobarb), steroids (increase vitamin D metabolism)  
- *Other rare forms*:  
  - Vitamin D-dependent rickets (genetic defect in 1⍺-hydroxylase or vitamin D receptor)  
  - Vitamin D-resistant rickets (familial hypophosphatemic rickets)  

*Clinical Features (high-yield)*:  
- Skeletal: Bow legs/knock knees, rachitic rosary (costochondral swelling), frontal bossing, delayed closure of fontanelles, widening of wrists and ankles  
- Growth retardation, delayed motor milestones  
- Craniotabes (soft skull bones)  
- Hypotonia  
- Dental enamel hypoplasia  

*Management*:  
- *Nutritional rickets (Vitamin D deficiency)*  
  - Vitamin D supplementation:  
    - 2,000 IU/day for 3 months OR  
    - Single stoss dose (daily practice varies; e.g. 150,000-600,000 IU single oral/IM dose)  
  - Calcium supplementation alongside vitamin D  
  - Adequate sunlight exposure  
- *Correction of underlying cause*: Treat malabsorption, renal/liver disease  
- *Genetic forms*: may need calcitriol (active vitamin D) or phosphate supplementation  
- *Prevention*:  
  - Vitamin D supplementation in exclusively breastfed infants (400 IU/day)  
  - Adequate maternal vitamin D during pregnancy/lactation  

== Poisoning in Children

=== General Principles
*Management of Accidental Poisoning*:  
- Ensure *Airway, Breathing, Circulation* (ABC) → stabilize first  
- Identify toxin (history, container, odor, clinical features)  
- Prevent further absorption:  
  - Gastric lavage (within 1 hr, if not contraindicated)  
  - Activated charcoal (1 g/kg) if toxin adsorbs + presentation within 1-2 hrs  
  - Avoid emetics (syrup of ipecac obsolete, and contraindicated in kerosene, corrosives, seizures, unconscious)  
- Enhance elimination (rare, toxin-specific: diuresis, alkalinization, dialysis)  
- Give specific antidote if available  
- Supportive and symptomatic care  
- Prevent recurrence: education, safe storage of drugs, poisons, kerosene  



=== Common Poisons

==== Organophosphorus (OPC) Poisoning
*Diagnosis* (cholinergic features → "DUMBELS"/"SLUDGE"):  
- *Muscarinic*: Diarrhea, Urination, Miosis, Bradycardia, Bronchorrhea, Emesis, Lacrimation, Salivation, Sweating  
- *Nicotinic*: Fasciculations, weakness, paralysis  
- *CNS*: Anxiety, convulsions, coma, respiratory depression  

*Management*:  
- ABCs (often ventilatory support needed due to muscle paralysis)  
- Decontamination (remove contaminated clothes, wash skin)  
- *Atropine*:  
  - Initial bolus IV 0.02-0.05 mg/kg, repeat every 5-10 min  
  - *Atropinization endpoint*: drying of secretions, clear chest on auscultation, HR >80-100/min, pupils mid-dilated (not miosis)  
- *Oximes (Pralidoxime, 25-50 mg/kg IV over 30 min, repeat 6-12 hrly)*: Reactivates acetylcholinesterase (if given early, before "aging")  
- Benzodiazepines for seizures  



==== Kerosene Poisoning
- Very common in children (accidental ingestion from beverage bottles)  
- *Pathophysiology*: Hydrocarbon aspiration → chemical pneumonitis; main risk is from vomiting → aspiration  
- *Clinical features*: Cough, choking, tachypnea, dyspnea, cyanosis; CNS depression in severe cases  
- *Management*:  
  - NO gastric lavage / NO induced vomiting (↑ risk aspiration)  
  - Supportive → airway, O2, fluids  
  - Bronchodilators, antibiotics only if proven secondary bacterial pneumonia  
  - Most cases resolve with supportive care  



==== Snake Bite
- *Types*:  
  - *Neurotoxic* (cobra, krait): ptosis, ophthalmoplegia, bulbar weakness, respiratory paralysis  
  - *Vasculotoxic* (viper): bleeding, DIC, renal failure, shock  
  - *Myotoxic* (sea snake): myoglobinuria, renal failure  

- *Management*:  
  - First aid: Immobilize limb, reassurance; NO tourniquet, NO incision/sucking  
  - ABCs, admit to hospital  
  - *Anti-snake venom (ASV)* if signs of envenomation (neuro signs, bleeding, shock, local swelling progressing)  
  - Supportive: respiratory support, dialysis if renal failure  
  - Tetanus prophylaxis, wound care  



== IMCI

*Definition*: *Integrated Management of Childhood Illness* - WHO/UNICEF strategy to reduce morbidity and mortality in < 5 children from common preventable conditions.

*Components*:  
- *Case management*: Standardized guidelines for assessment, classification, treatment, counseling  
- *Health system*: Drug supply, referral mechanisms  
- *Family/community practices*: Nutrition, immunization, compliance  

*Assessment of Sick Children*  
- *Check for General Danger Signs* (any → urgent referral):  
  - Inability to drink/breastfeed  
  - Vomiting everything  
  - Convulsions  
  - Lethargic or unconscious  



*Main Symptoms (IMCI covers)*  
=== Cough/Difficulty Breathing
- Ask duration, presence of stridor/wheezing  
- Assess RR (age-based cutoffs) + chest indrawing/stridor  

=== Diarrhea
- Ask duration, presence of blood  
- Assess dehydration (None / Some / Severe as per IMCI signs)  

=== Fever
- Ask for measles/malaria risk (endemic area, travel, seasonality)  
- Examine for stiff neck, measles rash, hepatosplenomegaly  

=== Ear Problems
- Ear pain, ear discharge, mastoid tenderness  



=== Classification and Treatment of Common Illness (per IMCI)

=== Pneumonia (Cough/breathing)
- *No pneumonia (cough/cold)* → Home care, supportive  
- *Pneumonia* → Fast breathing, no chest indrawing → Oral antibiotics (amoxicillin) + home care  
- *Severe pneumonia/disease* → Chest indrawing, stridor, danger sign → hospital admit, IV antibiotics, oxygen  

=== Diarrhea
- *No dehydration* → Plan A (home ORS, zinc, feeding)  
- *Some dehydration* → Plan B (ORS at facility, 75 ml/kg/4 hrs, reassess)  
- *Severe dehydration* → Plan C (IV RL/NS rehydration, urgent)  
- *Persistent/bloody diarrhea* → Evaluate/ treat as dysentery or persistent diarrhea  

=== Malaria
- In endemic zones:  
  - *No severe signs* → Oral ACT (Artemisinin combination therapy) as per national protocol  
  - *Severe malaria* → Admit, IV Artesunate (preferred) or IV Quinine if not available; manage hypoglycemia, seizures, fluids carefully  